<m2>By <m1> <m0>STEPHEN SMITH<ql>
Herald Staff Writer<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>   <m0>Y<m2><ql>
<m0>ou know it by a name that rings funny: mad cow disease, a deadly but rare ailment, found far away in England.<ep>
   Mayra Lichter knows it far more personally.<ep>
   Her father was stricken with the human variation, a little-known, little-understood condition called Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease. It killed him in four months, stunning his family, inspiring them to establish a national foundation in Miami devoted to understanding the disease and offering clues to families watching relatives slip into an abyss of dementia.<ep>
<m1>Someone to talk to<ep>
<m0>   ``I can't cure it, I can't give them hope, but I can give them someone to talk to,'' says Lichter, a former federal prosecutor. ``This isn't the kind of disease where we're going to have a telethon and a poster person and go around with cans soliciting donations.<ep>
   ``But I couldn't walk away from this disease. It was too mysterious, it was too devastating.''<ep>
   It has achieved newfound notoriety amid a British frenzy over the nation's beef stock. Researchers discovered in 1986 that disoriented cattle had been stricken with mad cow disease (--) known scientifically as bovine spongiform encephalopathy. <m1><ep>
<m1>Origins debated<ep>
<m0>   Debate has embroiled scientists since, with suspicions that the illness affecting British cattle lingers in beef sold at stores and can make humans sick. The condition humans develop: Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease. It is presumed, though not proved, that the 10 people felled in Britain are victims of the cow illness crossing the barrier into humans.<ep>
   But researchers believe in most cases of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, there is not such an obvious link. Striking roughly one person in a million, CJD is stealthy, believed to lurk in the body sometimes for decades before a fog of confusion drifts over the brain, blotting out old memories and altering personality.<ep>
<m1>Cases climbed<ep>
<m0>    Doctors at Jackson Memorial Hospital tracked cases from 1984 to 1993, uncovering an increase during that period. Between 1984 and 1989, there was an average of one case a year. The average climbed to 4.75 a year from 1990 to 1993.<ep>
   Writing in the journal Neurology, the researchers concluded that Creutzfeldt-Jakob ``may be increasing in incidence in our community.'' A teenager named Joseph Sardo helped the experts in their sleuthing. The disease claimed his father in 1989.<ep>
   ``I told my son, we've got to take a negative and make a positive out of it,'' says Cecile Sardo, who lives in South Dade.<ep>
